ce:section.ce:para:
The optical properties of CA-CDs were investigated through UV–vis absorption spectrum and fluorescence spectroscopy. It can be seen from Fig. S1 that CA-CDs have obvious absorption peaks in the range of 250 nm to 300 nm, which is owing to the CC group on the surface of CA-CDs. The maximum excitation wavelength of CA-CDs is 336 nm and the optimal emission wavelength is 446 nm. The fluorescence quantum yield of CA-CDs is 0.014. XPS analysis has been performed to gain the elemental composition of CA-CDs. There are only two elements, C and O, in CA-CDs. The relative contents of C and O were 58.98 % and 41.02 %, respectively ( Fig. S2
). NMR-13C resonance revealed the molecular structure of CA-CDs (Fig. 1 (c)). The signal at 100–150 ppm assigning to the sp2 hybrid carbon atom indicated the existence of CC in CA-CDs. The FT-IR absorption peaks of CA-CDs at 1633 cm−1 also proved that CC groups were formed on the surface of CA-CDs. The stretching vibration of the benzene ring = C H group (910 cm−1 to 665 cm−1), further confirmed the benzene ring structures on CA-CDs ( Fig. S3
). The wide (002) diffraction peak at around 26°in XRD patterns of the CA-CDs indicated the formation of graphitic structure in CA-CDs.

Incubation temperature and incubation time for CA-CDs-AA-TA system, TA concentration, and the pH value have been investigated to find the optimal conditions for the AA detection. Incubation at 55 °C for 15 min could make the system obtain the highest fluorescence intensity. The optimum incubation time was 15 min. When the final concentration of TA is higher than 5 mM, the fluorescence intensity increases slowly with TA concentration. Hence, 5 mM of TA is selected for subsequent experiments. CA-CDs exhibited excellent AAO mimetic activity at the pH value of 5.0 (
                           Fig. S5
                        ).

The steady-state kinetics of CA-CDs mimic enzyme performance was studied under optimal reaction conditions. The Michaelis–Menten constant (Km
                        ) reflects the affinity of the enzyme to the substrate. The specific step is to detect the change rate of the fluorescence intensity with time. The concentration of AA is used as the abscissa and the change rate of the fluorescence intensity is plotted as the ordinate. The calculated Km
                         of CA-CDs mimic enzyme is 1.9 × 10-4 M (Fig. 3

                        (a)). By comparing the steady-state kinetic parameters of CA-CDs with other AAO, the affinity of CA-CDs towards the AA is similar to that of natural AAO (
                           Table S1
                        ).

Based on the AAO activity of CA-CDs, a method for the detection of AA was established under optimal reaction conditions. The linear range of AA detection is 5.0 × 10-6 ∼ 1.0 × 10-4 M. The linear equation is F = 7.66678C-13.65009, R2 = 0.9977, and the detection limit is 1.5 × 10-7 M (Fig. 3
                        (b and c)). Compared with some reported methods, this proposed method has better sensitivity (Table 1
                        ). The natural enzyme-free detection platform is stable in wide pH range. The CA-CDs using CA as a single raw material are easy to prepare. The CA-CDs without metal doping avoid of heavy metal related pollutant. Furthermore, the signal-on mode for AA detection is simple.

Recovery experiments have been done to further prove the accuracy of the proposed method. The recoveries of the proposed method are between 93.75 and 107.14 % and the relative standard deviations are within 2.65 % (
                           Table S2
                        ). This further demonstrated the feasibility of the proposed method for AA determination in fruit juice and beverage samples.

The biocompatibility of CA-CDs in vitro was investigated by MTT assay. CA-CDs were cultured with Panc-1 and Hela cells for 24 h. MTT assay showed the cell viability reached more than 90.57 % (
                           Fig. S6
                        ). This results demonstrated that CA-CDs show lower cytotoxicity, which may be related to the absence of metal doping of CA-CDs.
